---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const tokenThemeExample = `:root {
    --colour-accent: #6f3cff;
    --colour-surface: #ffffff;
    --radius-card: 1rem;
}

@layer theme {
    .product-card {
        background: var(--colour-surface);
        border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    }
}`;

const goodThemeExample = `@layer theme {
    .button {
        --button-background: var(--colour-accent);
    }
}`;

const badThemeExample = `.button {
    background: purple;
}

.checkout-button {
    background: #7a32ff;
}

.hero-button {
    background: rgb(118 45 255);
}`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Theme Layer"
    description="Theme layer guidance for Layered Semantic CSS, including token-driven theming, safe visual overrides, and avoiding random one-off styling."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Theme layer</p>

        <h1>
            Theme layer
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            The theme layer handles brand-level visual overrides. It changes how
            components look, not how they work. Components own structure and
            behaviour. Theme owns presentation.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Theme layer sections">
        <a href="#purpose">Purpose</a>
        <a href="#tokens">Tokens first</a>
        <a href="#good-overrides">Good overrides</a>
        <a href="#avoid">Avoid</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="purpose" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            What belongs in the theme layer
        </h2>

        <p>
            Theme should contain brand styling, colour decisions, spacing
            adjustments, border radius changes, shadows, and other visual
            presentation choices that apply across components.
        </p>

        <p>
            Theme should not contain component logic, structural layout fixes,
            accessibility patches, or emergency overrides pretending not to be
            hacks.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="tokens" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Tokens first
        </h2>

        <p>
            Theme should be driven by shared CSS variables. Change the token,
            not twenty unrelated selectors. This keeps branding predictable and
            prevents colour drift across the project.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={tokenThemeExample} />
    </section>

    <section id="good-overrides" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Safe visual overrides
        </h2>

        <p>
            A good theme override adjusts presentation without rewriting the
            component. Prefer component-level custom properties where the
            component supports intentional visual configuration.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={goodThemeExample} />
    </section>

    <section id="avoid" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Avoid random one-off styling
        </h2>

        <p>
            If only one button becomes purple for unclear reasons, the problem
            is usually architecture, not branding. Random visual overrides make
            systems inconsistent and difficult to maintain.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={badThemeExample} />

        <ul>
            <li>Do not hard-code random colours inside components.</li>
            <li>Do not use theme as a hiding place for hacks.</li>
            <li>Do not override component structure from theme.</li>
            <li>Keep theme decisions intentional and documented.</li>
            <li>If the change is temporary, it belongs in hacks, not theme.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
